\cf2 \cb6 The plan marks a dramatic step forward in a long move by AT&T and other carriers toward a 21
\fs27 st
\fs36 \'a0century network infrastructure, signaling the final stage of convergence for old proprietary voice, video, and data networks to the open standards of a single IP network.\
Think of it as \'93Internet Everywhere.\'94\
Specifically, AT&T plans to retire much of its legacy copper networks running obsolete Time-Division Multiplexing (TDM) technology, replacing it with fiber optics transmitting all content as IP packets.\'a0 DSL Internet service will be replaced with high-speed broadband.\'a0 Slow and inefficient 3G and lower mobile networks, at the same time, will be upgraded to 4G LTE, in large part by deploying new \'93small cell\'94 technologies to better serve densely-populated areas.\
In a related development,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.att.com/Common/about_us/files/pdf/fcc_filing.pdf"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 the company also filed a petition with the FCC}}\'a0asking the agency to relax legacy regulations the company argues are impeding even faster retirement of legacy networks.\'a0 This despite the agency\'92s own clarion call, in the 2010\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.broadband.gov/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 National Broadband Plan}}\'a0(NBP), for carriers to quickly replace their aging copper physical plant with native IP running on fiber.\
