\f1\b\fs40 \cf2 Critics Miss the Point\'85Actually, Several of Them\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\sa288\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs36 \cf2 That great \'93infrastructure challenge\'94 has so far been met almost entirely with private funds.\'a0 And while AT&T Chairman Randall Stephenson made clear in his remarks that the company\'92s overall goal was to improve shareholder value, critics who dismissed the $14 billion investment plan as anti-consumer simply miss the point.\
The website GigaOM, for example,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://gigaom.com/2012/11/07/heres-atts-14b-plan-to-kill-its-copper-network-and-leave-rural-america-behind/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 harshly criticized the proposal}}\'a0as one that would leave rural customers without affordable basic telephone service, let alone Internet Everywhere.\'a0 But rural customers will not be abandoned as part of the plan.\'a0 Rather, many more will now have access to high-speed wired networks that rely in large part on fiber, with short copper loops serving the last mile.\
Instead of spinning off its rural customers, in fact, AT&T will spend billions bringing high-speed broadband to an additional 57 million customers through expansion of its U-verse technology.\'a0 For residents in areas where U-verse technologies will not be immediately deployed, the company has committed to providing an \'93economic path\'94 to broadband through wireless services based on high-speed 4G LTE networks.\
But in no case will residents in AT&T\'92s service area be left without affordable basic service.\'a0 Indeed, under existing federal and state regulation, the company must continue to offer any resident dial tone on demand, at prices often set by local regulatory agencies, even if that means serving those customers at a loss or continuing to maintain outmoded TDM networks.\
(Oddly, GigaOM\'92s founder Om Malik\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://gigaom.com/2012/11/07/hey-dsl-it-is-time-for-good-bye/?utm_source=social&utm_medium=twitter&utm_campaign=gigaom"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 later offered an opposing view}}, agreeing that \'93The puny Internet speeds [AT&T and Verizon] continued to offer via the old DSL has [sic] no part of this bandwidth-hungry future.\'94)\
