\f4\fs36 \cf2 \cb6 \strokec2 Other critics pointed to the $8 billion in additional investments in mobile network upgrades as proof that the \'93spectrum crunch\'94 repeatedly warned of by the FCC and others has been resolved or perhaps never existed.\'a0 In the NBP, the Commission projected that\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.forbes.com/sites/larrydownes/2012/08/27/the-fcc-scores-a-hat-trick-of-errors-on-internet-regulation/2/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 explosive increases in mobile demand would require}}\'a0300 Mhz. of new spectrum by 2015, and 500 Mhz. by 2020.\'a0 So far, almost no spectrum has been released by the agency, which continues to struggle in identifying public and private users from whom underutilized frequencies can be reclaimed.\
In today\'92s announcement, AT&T indicated that it now has sufficient spectrum to take the company past the 2015 horizon.\'a0 In part this has come through an aggressive campaign of acquisition in secondary markets, including the $1.9 billion purchase of unused spectrum from\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.forbes.com/companies/qualcomm/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 Qualcomm}}\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.forbes.com/sites/larrydownes/2011/12/23/the-fcc-changes-it-mind-about-spectrum-again/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 approved by the FCC last year}}.\'a0 The company\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://attpublicpolicy.com/fcc/fcc-approves-att-sirius-xm-wcs-spectrum-band-proposal/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 also recently resolved potential interference concerns}}\'a0with XM Sirius satellite radio that have kept it from making use of additional spectrum it held in the WCS band.\
But these hard-won successes do not remove the real risk of spectrum depletion if the FCC does not move quickly to free more capacity.\'a0 In the company\'92s presentation, shareholders were warned that beyond 2017, AT&T\'92s mobile networks must rely on the FCC to free spectrum from federal users and to successfully complete \'93voluntary incentive auctions\'94 aimed at encouraging over-the-air television broadcasters to return underutilized capacity in exchange for a share of auction proceeds.\
The agency has only just begun the process of designing these complex new auctions, and there is no precedent to suggest they will unleash any significant spectrum.\'a0 Meanwhile, federal users are continuing to stall in identifying warehoused and misused frequencies under their control,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-57481929-94/feds-to-mobile-users-drop-dead/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 despite a 2010 Executive Order from President Obama}}\'a0ordering them to do so.\'a0 And the essential deployment of new cell towers, antennae, and other infrastructure\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-20102911-94/does-your-iphone-service-suck-blame-city-hall/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 remains dependent on notoriously unresponsive local zoning}}\'a0authorities.\
Advocacy groups also crowed today that the announcement of $14 billion in additional investment proved that efforts by the FCC and other regulators to\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.forbes.com/sites/larrydownes/2012/06/06/the-fcc-noses-under-the-broadband-internet-tent/"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 inject themselves into the broadband ecosystem}}\'a0not only haven\'92t slowed private investment,\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324439804578104820999974556.html?mod=googlenews_wsj"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 \strokec5 but in fact are somehow encouraging it}}.\
But these self-serving claims are absurd on their face.\'a0 Indeed, AT&T made clear that it is targeting its investments to markets where it has seen clear signs of regulatory relief, and where the company can as a result expect to receive returns for its shareholders.\'a0 These include mobile networks, U-verse, and fiber deployments.\
